The "tracker style" version of Popcorn you're referring to is likely the MOD or S3M module common in the 90s demoscene. To convert it to your 6502 format, you need to map the four voices: typically Lead 1, Lead 2 (Echo/Counter), Bass, and Percussion.
1. The Notes (Main Theme)
The song is traditionally in G Minor (though many versions use B Minor). In G Minor, the catchy 7-note phrase for your Channel A is: [1] 

* Part 1 (The "Pop"): G F G D Bb D G (repeated)
* Part 2 (The Scale): G A Bb A Bb G A G A F G F G Eb G [1, 2, 3] 

2. The 4-Voice Layout
Since the Oric Atmos has 3 tone channels plus noise, you can map them like this:

* Channel A (Lead): The main melody using a staccato (short) envelope.
* Channel B (Bass/Chords): Alternating octaves of the root note. For G Minor, use G and D.
* Channel C (Echo or Counter): You can SLAVE this channel to play the same melody as Channel A but delayed by 1-2 frames at a lower volume to create that classic "popping" depth.
* Noise (Drums): Use your AYUPDATE or SETAYR commands on a timer to trigger noise bursts (R6) for the "snare" effect. [1, 4, 5] 

3. Conversion to Your Format
Using your nnnnn oct note encoding:

| Note | G | F | D | Bb |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Index (nnnnn) | 08 | 06 | 02 | 11 |
| Octave (ooo) | 4 | 4 | 4 | 3 |

Example Stream Fragment (Channel A):

    .byte $44 ; Note G (Index 8, Oct 4)
    .byte $34 ; Note F (Index 6, Oct 4)
    .byte $44 ; Note G (Index 8, Oct 4)
    .byte $14 ; Note D (Index 2, Oct 4)
    ...

4. Implementation Tip: The "Pop" Staccato
To get the authentic "pop" sound, don't just set the volume and leave it. Use a Volume Envelope Macro that drops the volume to zero very quickly after the note starts (e.g., Frame 1: Vol 15, Frame 2: Vol 8, Frame 3: Vol 0).
